  "prompt": "Mfc gui development future?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the future of MFC (Microsoft Foundation Classes) GUI development:\n\n1. Current Status\n- Still supported by Microsoft\n- Part of Visual Studio\n- Maintained for legacy Windows applications\n- Declining popularity\n\n2. Strengths\n- Native Windows development\n- Low overhead\n- Good performance\n- Compatible with older Windows systems\n- Familiar to long-time Windows developers\n\n3. Limitations\n- Aging framework\n- Less modern UI capabilities\n- Limited cross-platform support\n- Limited modern design patterns\n- Fewer new features\n\n4. Modern Alternatives\n- WPF (Windows Presentation Foundation)\n- Universal Windows Platform (UWP)\n- .NET MAUI\n- WinUI 3\n- Xamarin/.NET MAUI\n- Qt (cross-platform)\n\n5. Recommended Approaches\n- For new projects: Consider modern frameworks\n- For legacy maintenance: Continue with MFC\n- Gradual migration strategies\n- Hybrid approaches\n\n6. Future Recommendations\n- Learn modern UI frameworks\n- Keep MFC skills for maintenance\n- Explore cross-platform solutions\n- Stay updated with Microsoft development trends\n\n7. Potential Evolution\n- Potential modernization\n- Continued support for legacy applications\n- Gradual integration with newer technologies\n\nConclusion: MFC remains viable but not recommended for new development.",
